Here’s to raising babes in 2023 ✨ Don’t feel sorry for or fear for your kids because the world they are going to grow up in is not what it used to be.

God created them and called them for the exact moment in time that they’re in. Their life wasn’t a coincidence or an accident.

Raise them up to know the power they walk in as children of God.

Train them up in the authority of His Word.

Teach them to walk in faith knowing that God is in control.

Empower them to know they can change the world.

Don’t teach them to be fearful and disheartened by the state of the world but hopeful that they can do something about it.

Every person in all of history has been placed in the time that they were in because of God’s sovereign plan.

He knew Daniel could handle the lions’ den. 
He knew David could handle Goliath. 
He knew Esther could handle Haman. 
He knew Peter could handle persecution. 
He knows that your child can handle whatever challenge they face in their life. He created them specifically for it!

Don’t be scared for your children, but be honored that God chose you to parent the generation that is facing the biggest challenges of our lifetime. Rise up to the challenge.

Raise Daniels, Davids, Esthers, and Peters!

God isn’t scratching His head wondering what He’s going to do with this mess of a world.

He has an army He’s raising up to drive back the darkness and make Him known all over the earth.

Don’t let your fear steal the greatness God placed in them. I know it’s hard to imagine them as anything besides our sweet little babies, and we just want to protect them from anything that could ever be hard on them, but they were born for such a time as this. -

✨ Dream BIG dreams ✨ 

I’ve had a job since I was 14 (and before that working for my parents business #entrepreneurkid).. I’ve had jobs I’ve loved and others I hated but needed to pay bills. I worked my freaking butt off in high school + college with 2-3 jobs at a time and then was a special education teacher while getting my masters degree… and then I walked away from it all to stay home with our twins and started a little blog ❤️ 

7 years ago people laughed when I said I was starting a blog… and I make more money now than I ever would have as a teacher. I’ve prayed with women in DMs and planted seeds that have helped introduce women to Jesus. 

Almost 2 years ago I said ‘yes’ to an invitation to Young Living and friends and family literally laughed in my face….but y’all, we’re sponsoring kids we never could have dreamt of. We’re doing GOOD THINGS and my mind is constantly blown by what the Lord is doing. 

Dream. Dream the big dreams. The ones that make you scared and give you that pit in your stomach… the ones that are only possible because of God. The ones people laugh at.. and do it scared. But do it anyways. Literally no one’s opinions matter except yours and your husbands, and the Lord… and let me tell you, making money and supporting our family FROM MY PHONE… all the while homeschooling and being fully present with my family is A DREAM. So dream big, friends. ✨

✌🏼And if you want to see what this crazy dream is all about, shoot me a DM or comment MORE INFO and I got you… or if you’re here to hang and watch me fail, pull up a seat and grab some 🍿 cuz it’ll at least be a fun ride 🤪

I was unprepared for an unforeseen terrifying situation that could have ended so differently. Law enforcement was notified, and I thought quick enough to lie and say my husband was almost to the park, which spooked them enough to leave.

So what would I do differently??
1. Call 911 as soon as I saw the men come back (they had been yelling stupid things from their car a few minutes before, but had left the park).. I called my husband but ultimately, he couldn’t do anything - I should have called 911. 
2. Had some form of defense - ultimately, I want to be able to fully protect myself and my children… I know what I’m comfortable with and train to utilize that appropriately… you make that call for yourself.
3. Get details. A license plate. Descriptions of offenders. Say them out loud - law enforcement can use this!! 
4. Situational awareness - I did this well but I can’t stress this enough - BE AWARE OF YOUR SURROUNDINGS and trust your gut. If it feels off, it probably is. 
5. Be DIRECT: again, I did this well - bad guys don’t expect you to be firm and loud. 
6. Practice. I quickly learned my 4 year old was not prepared.. is it scary? Absolutely. But we live in a fallen world and I want my kids to be prepared. Practice solo. Practice with your kids. Have the hard conversations. 

I was SHOCKED at how many people have similar stories - feel free to drop them below 👇🏼 - I pray you never have something like this happen, but it’s why we prepare!! 

I don’t post this to instill fear, but to start the conversation around preparedness - we can prepare for situations from a place of empowerment, but it takes practice. It takes awareness. It takes facing your fears, head on, for the sake of your children, your life. I will protect my family with everything I have, but it’s not about being the strongest. We have to be prepared. 

I’m not an expert. I’m not in law enforcement. Im a mom to had the shit scared out of her and will do everything in my power to make sure I’m not in that situation again. Stay tuned.. I’m workin on something for us all ❤️

Here’s the thing:: I was a special education teacher.. I have my masters degree in special education with a minor in autism + applied behavior analysis - modifying environments was my JOB! .. but we all need the reminders so let’s start here: when a flower doesn’t bloom, you fix the environment in which the flower grows.. not the flower. ❤️ so here’s some hopefully helpful tips!
1. Allow your kiddo to complete tasks in “goofy” positions .. this is a way of self regulating their vestibular system!
2. Engage your kiddo in physical activity - things like push-ups, heavy work (carrying heavy things, lifting heavy things, dragging, pushing), giving firm hugs, etc… this helps regulate their proprioceptive system!
3. Break tasks up into smaller chunks + take breaks. 
4. Magnesium… We love a powder pixie stick type that has zero added sugar + tastes yummy!.. I have a book linked in my highlights I love that explains how much your kiddo (or you as an adult) needs!
5. Eliminate dyes + sugar - this was the hardest one and literally the best, most life changing switches we’ve made!

We go to the ocean every year but went to a new beach.. and while I very much respect the vastness + power of the ocean, the dangers that lie so close to the shore, in shallow water, never crossed my mind.. 

🌊 It happened so fast. The water was just past her knees and I was in the water with full eyes on her.. and it almost wasn’t enough. The rip current pulled her so fast and without warning. 

I started running to her and the depth changed so quickly, i fell and started swimming, but my purse was pulling me back. So I threw off my purse (with passports + phone) and swam as hard as I could and finally got to her. It felt like slow motion… I got her to safety and then lost it. 💔

In hindsight, the signs were there, we just didn’t know them. The water was “calm” where she was. It was darker. Her siblings were jumping the waves just 15 feet away… but it swept her feed under her and she couldn’t save herself. She screamed a gurgled scream I’ll never forget. 

If you’ve never experienced a rip current, there are signs. The current can knock you off your feet in even knee deep water. They say you should never run in to save someone caught in a rip current - you should swim parallel to the beach and you will get out… and I read an absurd amount of horrendous nightmares of adult and child drownings from the ocean. You must respect the ocean..

We learned lesson that day, to check for warnings. To be more aware of the signs and conditions before entering the ocean… and I’d encourage you to do the same. ❤️ we have an incredibly, beautiful world to explore but there are risks and dangers if you’re not aware. Praise Jesus, we all walked off that beach that day. ❤️
